5.2) Plot correlation heatmaps and MDS plots. Discuss the signal to noise ratio.

The heatmap shows high within-group correlation among replicates that received the same treatment, while lower correlations across groups, indicating that effects do vary as a function of particle size and concentration.

Accordingly, the MDS projection shows clear clustering of replicates according to particle size and amount. Altogether, both projections indicate a high signal-to-noise ratio, with low technical noise (= deviations among replicates of the same group) and strong biological signals separating treatment groups.

Correlation heatmap

Making expression_data as a matrix:

data_matrix <- as.matrix(expression_data[,row.names(metadata)])
row.names(data_matrix) <- expression_data$GeneSymbol

Plotting the heatmap:

correlation_heatmap <- cor(data_matrix, method = "spearman")
diag(correlation_heatmap) <- NA # removes the diagonal
Heatmap(correlation_heatmap,
        row_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8),
        column_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8))

MDS projection

Changing the treatment names for better readability in the graph:

metadata_simplified <- metadata %>%
  mutate(treatment = treatment %>%
           # Replace "silicon dioxide nanoparticle" with "SiO2"
           str_replace_all("silicon dioxide nanoparticle", "SiO2 NPs") %>%
           # Extract particle size (e.g., "500 nm") and keep it
           str_replace_all("with (\\d+) nm silica particles", "+ \\1nm silica particles") %>%
           # Extract dose (e.g., "delivered at dose 50 ug/mL") and shorten it
           str_replace_all("delivered at dose (\\d+) ug/mL", "\\1g/mL") %>%
           # Remove unnecessary words like "and"
           str_replace_all(" and ", ", ")
  )

Plotting the MDS plot:

data.frame(cmdscale(dist(2-correlation_heatmap),eig=TRUE, k=2)$points) |>
  add_column(treatment = metadata_simplified$treatment) |>
  rownames_to_column("sample") |>
  mutate(replicate = str_extract(sample, "\\d+$")) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=X1,y=X2)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=treatment)) +
  geom_text(aes(label=replicate)) +
  theme_bw()

5.3) Report your model matrix (heatmap) and describe each coefficient in terms of which conditions is going to compare.
Setting up the model matrix 
metadata_simplified <- metadata_simplified |> 
  mutate(treatment = as.factor(treatment)) |> 
  mutate(treatment = relevel(treatment, ref = "reference substance role"))
levels(metadata_simplified$treatment)
## [1] "reference substance role"                    
## [2] "SiO2 NPs + 10nm silica particles, 20g/mL"   
## [3] "SiO2 NPs + 10nm silica particles, 50g/mL"   
## [4] "SiO2 NPs + 500nm silica particles, 20g/mL"  
## [5] "SiO2 NPs + 500nm silica particles, 50g/mL"  
## [6] "SiO2 NPs 5g/mL"                             
## [7] "SiO2 NPs with 500 nm silica particle, 5g/mL"
model_matrix <- model.matrix(~ treatment, data = metadata_simplified)
colnames(model_matrix) <- sub("^treatment", "", colnames(model_matrix))

Intercept corresponds to untreated cells treated with a reference substance control and treatments corresponds to all treatment conditions, i.e.SiO2 nanoparticles conjugated to 10nM or 500nm silica particles at 50g/mL, 20g/mL, or 5g/mL.

pheatmap(model_matrix)

5.4) Provide your volcano plot and p-value distribution. Do you see significant differences? In which conditions (if you have many). How many significant genes do you find?
Data normalization and differential expression 
dataVoom <- voom(data_matrix, design=model_matrix, plot = TRUE)

limmaFit <- lmFit(dataVoom, design=model_matrix)
limmaFit <- eBayes(limmaFit)
limmaRes <- list() 
for(coefx in colnames(coef(limmaFit))){ 
  print(coefx)
  limmaRes[[coefx]] <- topTable(limmaFit, coef=coefx,number = Inf) |>
    rownames_to_column("gene")
}
## [1] "(Intercept)"
## [1] "SiO2 NPs + 10nm silica particles, 20g/mL"
## [1] "SiO2 NPs + 10nm silica particles, 50g/mL"
## [1] "SiO2 NPs + 500nm silica particles, 20g/mL"
## [1] "SiO2 NPs + 500nm silica particles, 50g/mL"
## [1] "SiO2 NPs 5g/mL"
## [1] "SiO2 NPs with 500 nm silica particle, 5g/mL"
limmaRes <- bind_rows(limmaRes, .id = "coef")
limmaRes <- filter(limmaRes, coef != "(Intercept)")

From the volcano plot, a significant difference in log fold changes (i.e.changes in relation to control) can be seen for 10nm silica nanoparticles in both concentrations, while 500nm nanoparticles seem to cause significant differences only at higher concentrations.

As indicated by the P-value distribution, all genes are highly expressed (minimum AveExpr of 4.9) with no outliers, thus no need for filtering.

Volcano plot:

ggplot(
  data = limmaRes,

Plotting expression data 
dat.list <- list()
for(gg in goi.all){
  dat.list[[gg]] <- metadata_simplified |>
    mutate(E=scale(dataVoom$E[gg,])) |>
    rownames_to_column("sample") |>
    remove_rownames()
} 
(p.vals <- bind_rows(dat.list, .id = "ID") |>
    mutate(
      sample = as.character(sample),
      
      # extract rep number for x-axis
      sample_label = str_extract(sample, "(?i)rep\\s*\\d+") %>%
        str_replace_all("\\s+", "") %>%
        trimws(),
      
      # create label WITHOUT rep numbers
      treatment_clean = sample %>%
        str_remove("(?i)rep\\s*\\d+") %>%   # remove "rep1"/"rep 1"
        str_remove(",\\s*$") %>%            # remove comma and spaces
        str_replace_all("_$", "") %>%       # remove trailing underscores
        str_trim()
    ) |>
    ggplot(aes(x = sample_label, y = ID, fill = E)) +
    geom_tile() +
    facet_grid(
      . ~ treatment_clean,
      space = "free",
      scales = "free",
      labeller = labeller(treatment_clean = function(x) str_wrap(x, width = 12))
    ) +
    scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red") +
    labs(x = "Replicates per treatment group", y = "Genes", fill = "Expression") +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
      panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA, size = 1),
      axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)
    )
)

5.6) Perform enrichment analysis. Are the results expected biologically (do you see expected pathways regulated)?
Enrichment analysis for each coefficient 
fisher_list <- list()
for(coefx in unique(limmaResSig$coef)){
  
  # What is coefx now?
  message(coefx)
  
  # Extract genes of interests (GOI) for a given coefficient (see yesterday's example)
  goi <- limmaResSig %>% filter(coef == coefx) %>% pull(ID) |> unique()
  
  universe <- limmaResSig$ID |> unique()
  universe <- universe[!is.na(universe) & universe != ""]
  MSigDB <- readRDS("MSigDB.rds")
  fisher_tbl <- map_df(names(MSigDB), function(pw) {
    pw_genes <- MSigDB[[pw]]
    sig_genes <- goi
    overlap <- intersect(sig_genes, pw_genes)
    a <- length(overlap)
    b <- length(sig_genes) - a
    c <- length(pw_genes) - a
    d <- length(universe) - (a+b+c)
    
    ft <- fisher.test(matrix(c(a,b,c,d),2), alternative = "greater")
    
    tibble(
      pathway = pw,
      pvalue = ft$p.value,
      odds_ratio = as.numeric(ft$estimate),
      DE_in_pathway = a,
      overlapping_genes = paste(overlap, collapse = ",")
    )
  })
  fisher_tbl <- fisher_tbl |> mutate(p_adj = p.adjust(pvalue, "BH"))
  print(head(fisher_tbl))
  
  # Store results in the list
  fisher_list[[coefx]] <- fisher_tbl
}

(top3_expression <- bind_rows(dat.list, .id = "ID") |>
    mutate(
      sample = as.character(sample),
      
      # extract rep number for x-axis
      sample_label = str_extract(sample, "(?i)rep\\s*\\d+") %>%
        str_replace_all("\\s+", "") %>%
        trimws(),
      
      # create label WITHOUT rep numbers
      treatment_clean = sample %>%
        str_remove("(?i)rep\\s*\\d+") %>%   # remove "rep1"/"rep 1"
        str_remove(",\\s*$") %>%            # remove comma and spaces
        str_replace_all("_$", "") %>%       # remove trailing underscores
        str_trim()
    ) |>
    ggplot(aes(x = sample_label, y = ID, fill = E)) +
    geom_tile() +
    facet_grid(
      . ~ treatment_clean,
      space = "free",
      scales = "free",

top3_statistics + top3_expression

By observing expression data and statistics on log fold changes and P values of Rhob, Nr4a2 and Cxcl2, its possible to observe that 10nm silica particles cause the most proeminent upregulating effect at high and mid doses.

Indeed, the authors declared that (size-specific) gene expression changes were identified, although the overall biological processes represented by all gene expression changes were nearly identical, irrespective of particle diameter - honestly Im not sure what they mean here.

Nr4a2, a receptor previously reported to play a role in inflammatory response by reducing inflammatory gene expression in cells of the central nervous system, shows strong up-regulation after nanoparticle treatment and remains relatively stable in control samples. This expression pattern is consistent with NR4A2s known role as an inducible transcription factor that maintains baseline activity and can rapidly respond to cellular stress.

Cxcl2, on the other hand, is mildly up-regulated in response to particle treatment and shows very low expression in untreated controls. This may be interpreted as the outcome of a rapid, less aggressive inflammatory/chemokine response in comparison to Nr4a2, but functional follow-up experiments would be required to confirm a role.

Finally, the high expression of Rhob in 10nm treatments is consistent with stress response upon nanoparticle exposure and/or changes in membrane dynamics, e.g.nanoparticle uptake. The moderate basal expression is consistent with the role of Rhob as a rapid-response regulator rather than an important modulator (as it is the case for Nr4a2) - but again, functional experiments would be needed in order to confirm this.
